13:54.067 --> 13:58.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What effect did he have on the
court, how
the Constitution is interpreted
and how cases

13:58.738 --> 14:00.573 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are decided?

14:00.673 --> 14:04.844 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown gets an
assessment, and he starts
with some of Justice Scalia's
own thoughts

14:04.944 --> 14:06.946 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and comments in prior
interviews.

14:07.046 --> 14:12.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Over the years,
Antonin Scalia
found occasions to speak
publicly of his judicial

14:12.385 --> 14:14.053 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
philosophy.

14:14.153 --> 14:19.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Late in 2012, with the release
of his book
"Reading Law: The Interpretation
of Legal

14:19.358 --> 14:21.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Text," he said this to Charlie
Rose:

14:21.327 --> 14:24.097 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ANTONIN SCALIA, Associate
Justice, U.S. Supreme
Court: The key question is
simply this. Would

14:24.197 --> 14:31.304 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the American people have
ratified the document
if it said, the application of
this document

14:31.404 --> 14:37.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and what it means shall be
whatever the Supreme
Court says it means from age to
age? Nobody

14:37.977 --> 14:40.580 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- nobody would have ratified
that document.

14:40.680 --> 14:44.450 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLIE ROSE, Host, "The Charlie
Rose Show":
It's a dead document to you?

14:44.550 --> 14:47.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANTONIN SCALIA: I like to say an
enduring
document.

14:48.087 --> 14:49.288 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

14:49.388 --> 14:51.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLIE ROSE: But you don't say
it's a living
document.

14:51.724 --> 14:53.793 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANTONIN SCALIA: It's not living.
It's not
living.

14:53.893 --> 14:58.364 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: In that
conversation and others,
the justice also explained his
thinking on

14:58.464 --> 15:04.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some pivotal decisions and
dissents, including
the bitterly debated ruling that
decided the

15:04.370 --> 15:06.405 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
2000 presidential election, Bush
v. Gore.

15:06.506 --> 15:10.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLIE ROSE: They think it was
a political
decision because the politics of
the country

15:10.543 --> 15:15.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
made you say we got to do this
the way we
did it in order to get this over
with. The

15:15.748 --> 15:19.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
court decided that, in the
interest of the
national -- in the national
interests, they

15:19.819 --> 15:20.953 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
got to get this over with.

15:21.053 --> 15:22.889 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

15:22.989 --> 15:27.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTONIN SCALIA: The remedy for a
case is always
subject to the court's
discretion, and always

15:27.393 --> 15:34.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
depends upon realities on the
ground, not
the law, but what the remedy
will be, whether

15:34.734 --> 15:39.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you tell them do it immediately,
give them
another two weeks. That's not an
issue of

15:39.272 --> 15:41.240 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
law. It's an issue of
practicality.

15:41.340 --> 15:46.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Earlier that
year, Justice
Scalia spoke to the "NewsHour"'s
Margaret

15:46.512 --> 15:51.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Warner, discussing his dissent
in the court's
ruling in favor of President
Obama's health

15:51.217 --> 15:55.154 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
care law, which cited the
government's power
to tax and impose penalties.

15:55.254 --> 16:00.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTONIN SCALIA: The issue is not
whether Congress
has the power to tax. The issue
is whether,

16:00.660 --> 16:06.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in this particular law, Congress
was exercising
the power to tax.

16:06.199 --> 16:15.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in all of our prior cases,
we said that,
even if you call it a tax, if
it's being imposed

16:15.808 --> 16:22.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the violation of a law, it's
a penalty.
And this one wasn't even called
a tax. It

16:22.515 --> 16:24.283 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was called a penalty.

16:24.383 --> 16:27.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Justice Scalia,
the child of
Italian immigrants and first
Italian-American

16:27.987 --> 16:33.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the court, also spoke of his
heritage,
as here in a 2015 PBS
documentary.

16:33.526 --> 16:40.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTONIN SCALIA: I think for
Italian-Americans,
given what they most abhor,
which is their

16:40.666 --> 16:48.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
identification with crime and
the mafia, I
wouldn't be surprised if they
would be more

16:48.374 --> 16:54.413 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
proud to have an
Italian-American justice
than to have an Italian-American
president.

16:54.513 --> 16:59.752 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: And now
reflections from three
legal scholars who head research
groups.

16:59.852 --> 17:04.156 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Edward Whelan of the
conservative Ethics and
Public Policy Center, he worked
as a law clerk

17:04.257 --> 17:09.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to Justice Scalia in 1991 and
'92. Elizabeth
Wydra heads the progressive
Constitutional

17:09.896 --> 17:15.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Accountability Center, and
Jeffrey Rosen of
George Washington University and
the nonpartisan

17:15.234 --> 17:18.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
National Constitution Center in
Philadelphia.

17:18.271 --> 17:20.072 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome to all three of you.

17:20.172 --> 17:25.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I want to start first with his,
Justice Scalia's
influence on jurisprudence, how
cases are

17:25.444 --> 17:27.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
talked about, how they're
decided.

17:27.313 --> 17:32.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Edward Whelan, you worked with
him. You saw
him in action. This idea of
originalism, how

17:32.585 --> 17:34.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
did he push it? What impact did
it have?

17:34.420 --> 17:38.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EDWARD WHELAN, Ethics and Public
Policy Center:
Well, he pushed it both as a
judge and as

17:39.091 --> 17:40.860 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
an academic.

17:40.960 --> 17:45.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he pushed it through his
opinions. The
basic principle of textualism is
that a text

17:45.197 --> 17:51.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has a meaning to be discerned.
That's true
of the Constitution, where
originalism provides,

17:51.470 --> 17:56.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one seeks to figure out what the
meaning of
a constitutional provision was
at the time

17:56.842 --> 17:58.644 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it was adopted, likewise with
statutes.

17:58.744 --> 18:03.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One looks to decide -- to figure
out what
a meaning of the text is there.
He had tremendous

18:03.616 --> 18:07.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
influence on the Supreme Court
in moving it
away from reliance on
legislative history,

18:08.054 --> 18:13.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
especially the look to
legislative history
first to determine what a
statute means.

18:13.926 --> 18:17.763 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he also, I think, had
considerable influence
on constitutional
interpretation, including

18:17.863 --> 18:22.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
perhaps most markedly in the
Heller Second
Amendment case in 2008.

18:22.168 --> 18:26.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Elizabeth Wydra,
you're on
the other side of Justice Scalia
on most legal

18:26.272 --> 18:31.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issues, but did he change the
way you think
about the law, the way you argue
it?

18:31.410 --> 18:33.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELIZABETH WYDRA, Constitutional
Accountability
Center: Yes, absolutely.

18:33.312 --> 18:37.783 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I -- as a progressive, I
disagreed with Justice
Scalia on many, if not most of
the outcomes

18:37.883 --> 18:43.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of cases. But I absolutely agree
with his
embrace of the Constitution's
text and history.

18:43.990 --> 18:50.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And my organization, the
Constitutional Accountability
Center, was very much informed
by, or I guess

18:50.296 --> 18:54.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
formed almost in a reaction to
Justice Scalia's
strong embrace of text and
history.

18:54.800 --> 18:55.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Formed in
reaction, right?

18:55.935 --> 18:57.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ELIZABETH WYDRA: I mean, in
part, certainly.

18:57.770 --> 19:03.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But as he strongly advocated for
conservative
outcomes based on the text and
history in

19:03.642 --> 19:10.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Supreme Court, progressives
like me and
like CAC, my organization, were
inspired to

19:10.149 --> 19:14.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
say no from our perspective.
Let's disagree
on this, but let's talk about
that text and

19:14.420 --> 19:16.188 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
history.

19:16.288 --> 19:17.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when we look at it, we think
it supports
progressive outcomes. But we
were having a

19:17.990 --> 19:20.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
debate with each other. We were
not arguing
past each other.

19:20.659 --> 19:22.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In other words,
you're saying
he may be right about the way of
thinking

19:22.928 --> 19:24.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about the law, but he's still
wrong on the
outcome.

19:24.897 --> 19:25.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WYDRA: Right.

19:26.065 --> 19:27.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you are
arguing on his
terms?

19:27.533 --> 19:29.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELIZABETH WYDRA: Well, I think
we're arguing
on the same terms...

19:29.201 --> 19:30.536 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: OK.

19:30.636 --> 19:32.505 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WYDRA: ... the
Constitution, which
belongs to everyone.

19:32.605 --> 19:36.442 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think it was a good
example of how Americans
can argue about the meaning of
the Constitution

19:36.542 --> 19:41.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and really go toe to toe on
whether this is
a progressive document, as I
think, or a conservative

19:41.113 --> 19:43.049 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
one.

19:43.149 --> 19:45.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Jeffrey Rosen,
what would you
add to this? This is also a
justice who famously,

19:45.284 --> 19:49.455 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
"I'm an originalist and a
textualist, not
a nut." Right?

19:49.555 --> 19:51.390 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Explain what he meant by that?

19:51.490 --> 19:53.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY ROSEN, Law Professor,
George Washington
University: He meant that in a
good sense.

19:53.526 --> 19:58.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was talking about his friend
Justice Thomas,
and he said, "Unlike Justice
Thomas, I wouldn't

19:58.297 --> 20:02.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
overturn every case that I think
is inconsistent
with original understanding,
because I'm not

20:02.301 --> 20:04.203 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a nut."

20:04.303 --> 20:07.840 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he meant that very
affectionately. But
despite that pragmatism, the
fact that progressive

20:07.940 --> 20:12.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
organizations like the wonderful
Constitutional
Accountability Center were
founded that text

20:12.878 --> 20:17.349 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in history could lead to
progressive, as well
as conservative results is a
sign of Scalia's

20:17.450 --> 20:19.318 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
incredible influence.

20:19.418 --> 20:23.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He must be counted one of the
most influential
and significant justices of the
20th century,

20:23.322 --> 20:27.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because he changed the terms of
constitutional
debate. He forced progressives
to make those

20:27.660 --> 20:29.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
arguments and to try to beat him
at his own
game.

20:29.895 --> 20:34.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, sometimes, progressives
argue Justice
Scalia was an inconsistent
originalist, ignoring

20:34.567 --> 20:38.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the text and history in case
like Brown vs.
Board of Education, which is
hard to justify

20:38.704 --> 20:43.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on originalist grounds. Scalia's
response
was essentially, no theory is
perfect. I may

20:43.576 --> 20:47.246 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
not be able to justify
everything, but basically
I'm pretty good.

20:47.346 --> 20:52.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's really important to
note, too, the
series of cases where Scalia's
preferences

20:52.418 --> 20:57.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
diverged from his constitutional
preferences,
flag burning, the rights of
criminal defendants,

20:57.423 --> 21:01.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the right to confront your
accusers, the independent
counsel law. These are all cases
that favored

21:01.994 --> 21:05.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
liberal results because Scalia
felt the Constitution
compelled it.

21:05.698 --> 21:09.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for distinguishing policy
arguments and
constitutional arguments, I
think he deserves

21:09.635 --> 21:11.370 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
great respect.

21:11.470 --> 21:13.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, so we
asked all
three of you to come up, to
think about a

21:13.272 --> 21:16.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
key case and a few lines that
help illustrate
his thinking.

21:16.208 --> 21:18.144 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Let me start with you, Ed, Ed
Whelan.

21:18.244 --> 21:24.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You chose something from the
famous Casey
case, the Planned Parenthood vs.
Casey. So,

21:24.450 --> 21:29.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the lines are, "By foreclosing
all democratic
outlet for the deep passions
this issue arouses,

21:29.889 --> 21:33.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by banishing the issue from the
political
forum that gives all
participants, even the

21:33.692 --> 21:38.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
losers, the satisfaction of a
fair hearing
and an honest fight, by
continuing the imposition

21:38.464 --> 21:42.668 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of a rigid national rule,
instead of allowing
for regional differences, the
court merely

21:42.768 --> 21:45.938 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
prolongs and intensifies the
anguish."

21:46.038 --> 21:47.773 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why did you pick those lines?

21:47.873 --> 21:53.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EDWARD WHELAN: Well, I think
that passage
captures Justice Scalia's belief
that so many

21:54.013 --> 22:00.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issues that other people want to
constitutionalize
are really left to the political
processes

22:00.986 --> 22:03.822 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to decide one way or the other.

22:03.923 --> 22:09.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People often caricature Justice
Scalia as
a conservative, when in fact on
a whole host

22:09.995 --> 22:15.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of issues, whether it's
abortion, the death
penalty, same-sex marriage, his
position is

22:15.734 --> 22:20.606 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
not that the Constitution
entrenches his own
views, but rather that it leaves
the matter

22:20.706 --> 22:22.474 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to democratic processes.

22:22.575 --> 22:27.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's his ultimate humility about
the judicial
role and the sharp line drawn
between the

22:28.047 --> 22:32.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
role of the courts and the role
of the elected
branches.

22:32.418 --> 22:35.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you say that
running through
all his decisions and dissents?

22:35.821 --> 22:39.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EDWARD WHELAN: That's certainly
a basic theme.
Obviously, there are plenty of
times when

22:39.725 --> 22:43.862 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he saw that there were popular
enactments
that violated the Constitution.

22:43.963 --> 22:50.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The key challenge, I think, of
any justice
is to discern the line between
what the Constitution

22:51.070 --> 22:55.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allows and what it forbids and
to avoid imposing
one's own policy preferences.

22:55.774 --> 23:00.145 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right,
Elizabeth Wydra,
now, you picked one, a quote
from a case,

23:00.246 --> 23:02.081 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Crawford v. Washington.

23:02.181 --> 23:07.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's -- this is writing the
opinion for
the court -- "Dispensing with
confrontation

23:07.820 --> 23:13.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because testimony is obviously
reliable is
akin to dispensing with a jury
trial because

23:13.859 --> 23:19.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the defendant is obviously
guilty. This is
not what the Sixth Amendment
prescribes. "

23:19.331 --> 23:21.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why that? What does that tell
you about his
thinking?

23:21.267 --> 23:25.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WYDRA: Well, Justice
Scalia, as
I mentioned earlier, was a
conservative justice,

23:25.971 --> 23:31.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but there were areas in which
progressives
and conservatives could agree
with his jurisprudence.

23:31.844 --> 23:36.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And criminal procedure and
criminal law were
some of those areas. And that
case shows that,

23:36.615 --> 23:42.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in some cases, he was quite the
friend to
criminal defendants and was very
strong on

23:42.121 --> 23:46.258 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ensuring that jury protections
to criminal
defendants were afforded.

23:46.358 --> 23:49.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then there were other cases,
for example,
on the Fourth Amendment search
and seizure

23:49.561 --> 23:56.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
context, where he struck down
law enforcement
techniques that violated the
privacy and the

23:56.568 --> 24:02.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
founders' original idea that
your person,
papers and effects should be
kept private.

24:02.207 --> 24:07.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, he isn't generally thought
of as a friend
to the less powerful -- and I
think in most

24:07.146 --> 24:11.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cases he wasn't -- but certainly
in the criminal
defense area, he was from time
to time in

24:11.417 --> 24:13.652 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very important ways. And I think
that's a
big part of his legacy.

24:13.752 --> 24:15.087 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right.

24:15.187 --> 24:17.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, Jeffrey Rosen, you're from
a dissent
in the Dickerson case.

24:17.890 --> 24:24.163 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And Scalia's words were:
"Today's judgment
converts Miranda from a
milestone of judicial

24:24.263 --> 24:30.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
overreaching into the very
Cheops Pyramid
or perhaps the Sphinx would be a
better analogue

24:30.803 --> 24:32.671 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of judicial arrogance."

24:32.771 --> 24:36.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, you can parse the legal
part, but I suspect
you picked it because of the --
it shows a

24:36.875 --> 24:38.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
